#. Tag: title
#: troubleshooting.xml:475
#, no-c-format
msgid "Boot Problems"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:477
#, no-c-format
msgid "Boot problems are situations when your system does not boot properly (does not boot to the expected target and login screen)."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: troubleshooting.xml:483
#, no-c-format
msgid "The &grub; Boot Loader Fails to Load"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:484
#, no-c-format
msgid "If the hardware is functioning properly, it is possible that the boot loader is corrupted and Linux cannot start on the machine. In this case, it is necessary to repair the boot loader. To do so, you need to start the Rescue System as described in <xref linkend=\"sec.trouble.data.recover.rescue\"/> and follow the instructions in <xref linkend=\"sec.trouble.data.recover.rescue.grub\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:492
#, no-c-format
msgid "Alternatively, you can use the Rescue System to fix the boot loader as follows. Boot your machine from the installation media. In the boot screen, choose <menuchoice><guimenu>More</guimenu> <guimenu>Boot Linux System</guimenu></menuchoice> . Select the disk containing the installed system and kernel with the default kernel options."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: troubleshooting.xml:501
#, no-c-format
msgid "Select Disk"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:512
#, no-c-format
msgid "When the system is booted, start &yast; and switch to <menuchoice><guimenu>System</guimenu> <guimenu>Boot Loader</guimenu></menuchoice> . Make sure that the <guimenu>Write generic Boot Code to MRB</guimenu> option is enabled, and click <guimenu>OK</guimenu> . This fixes the corrupted boot loader by overwriting it, or installs the boot loader if it is missing."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:521
#, no-c-format
msgid "Other reasons for the machine not booting may be BIOS-related:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: troubleshooting.xml:526
#, no-c-format
msgid "BIOS Settings"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:528
#, no-c-format
msgid "Check your BIOS for references to your hard disk. &grub; may simply not be started if the hard disk itself cannot be found with the current BIOS settings."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: troubleshooting.xml:536
#, no-c-format
msgid "BIOS Boot Order"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:538
#, no-c-format
msgid "Check whether your system's boot order includes the hard disk. If the hard disk option was not enabled, your system may install properly, but fails to boot when access to the hard disk is required."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: troubleshooting.xml:549
#, no-c-format
msgid "No Login or Prompt Appears"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:550
#, no-c-format
msgid "This behavior typically occurs after a failed kernel upgrade and it is known as a <emphasis>kernel panic</emphasis> because of the type of error on the system console that sometimes can be seen at the final stage of the process. If, in fact, the machine has just been rebooted following a software update, the immediate goal is to reboot it using the old, proven version of the Linux kernel and associated files. This can be done in the &grub; boot loader screen during the boot process as follows:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:561
#, no-c-format
msgid "Reboot the computer using the reset button, or switch it off and on again."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:567
#, no-c-format
msgid "When the &grub; boot screen becomes visible, select the <guimenu>Advanced Options</guimenu> entry and choose the previous kernel from the menu. The machine will boot using the prior version of the kernel and its associated files."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:575
#, no-c-format
msgid "After the boot process has completed, remove the newly installed kernel and, if necessary, set the default boot entry to the old kernel using the &yast; <guimenu>Boot Loader</guimenu> module. For more information refer to <xref linkend=\"sec.grub2.yast2.config\"/> . However, doing this is probably not necessary because automated update tools normally modify it for you during the rollback process."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:585
#, no-c-format
msgid "Reboot."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:590
#, no-c-format
msgid "If this does not fix the problem, boot the computer using the installation media. After the machine has booted, continue with <xref linkend=\"st.trouble.boot.hang.modify_grub\" xrefstyle=\"StepOnPage\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: troubleshooting.xml:598
#, no-c-format
msgid "No Graphical Login"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:599
#, no-c-format
msgid "If the machine starts, but does not boot into the graphical login manager, anticipate problems either with the choice of the default systemd target or the configuration of the X Window System. To check the current systemd default target run the command <command>sudo systemctl get-default</command> . If the value returned is <emphasis>not</emphasis> <literal>graphical.target</literal> , run the command <command>sudo systemctl isolate graphical.target</command> . If the graphical login screen starts, log in and start <menuchoice> <guimenu>&yast;</guimenu> <guimenu>System</guimenu> <guimenu>&ycc_runlevel;</guimenu></menuchoice> and set the <guimenu>Default System Target</guimenu> to <guimenu>Graphical Interface</guimenu> . From now on the system should boot into the graphical login screen."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:613
#, no-c-format
msgid "If the graphical login screen does not start even if having booted or switched to the graphical target, your desktop or X Window software is probably misconfigured or corrupted. Examine the log files at <filename>/var/log/Xorg.*.log</filename> for detailed messages from the X server as it attempted to start. If the desktop fails during start, it may log error messages to the system journal that can be queried with the command <command>journalctl</command> (see <xref linkend=\"cha.journalctl\"/> for more information). If these error messages hint at a configuration problem in the X server, try to fix these issues. If the graphical system still does not come up, consider reinstalling the graphical desktop."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: troubleshooting.xml:641
#, no-c-format
msgid "Root Btrfs Partition Cannot Be Mounted"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:642
#, no-c-format
msgid "If a <systemitem class=\"filesystem\">btrfs</systemitem> root partition becomes corrupted, try the following options:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:648
#, no-c-format
msgid "Mount the partition with the <option>-o recovery</option> option."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:654
#, no-c-format
msgid "If that fails, run <command>btrfs-zero-log</command> on your root partition."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: troubleshooting.xml:663
#, no-c-format
msgid "Force Checking Root Partitions"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:665
#, no-c-format
msgid "If the root partition becomes corrupted, use the parameter <parameter>forcefsck</parameter> on the boot prompt. This passes the option <option>-f</option> (force) to the <command>fsck</command> command."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: troubleshooting.xml:673
#, no-c-format
msgid "Login Problems"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:675
#, no-c-format
msgid "Login problems occur when your machine does boot to the expected welcome screen or login prompt, but refuses to accept the user name and password, or accepts them but then does not behave properly (fails to start the graphic desktop, produces errors, drops to a command line, etc.)."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: troubleshooting.xml:683
#, no-c-format
msgid "Valid User Name and Password Combinations Fail"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:684
#, no-c-format
msgid "This usually occurs when the system is configured to use network authentication or directory services and, for some reason, cannot retrieve results from its configured servers. The <systemitem class=\"username\">root</systemitem> user, as the only local user, is the only user that can still log in to these machines. The following are some common reasons a machine appears functional but cannot process logins correctly:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:695
#, no-c-format
msgid "The network is not working. For further directions on this, turn to <xref linkend=\"sec.trouble.netconfig\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:701
#, no-c-format
msgid "DNS is not working at the moment (which prevents &gnome; from working and the system from making validated requests to secure servers). One indication that this is the case is that the machine takes an extremely long time to respond to any action. Find more information about this topic in <xref linkend=\"sec.trouble.netconfig\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:710
#, no-c-format
msgid "If the system is configured to use Kerberos, the system's local time may have drifted past the accepted variance with the Kerberos server time (this is typically 300 seconds). If NTP (network time protocol) is not working properly or local NTP servers are not working, Kerberos authentication ceases to function because it depends on common clock synchronization across the network."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:720
#, no-c-format
msgid "The system's authentication configuration is misconfigured. Check the PAM configuration files involved for any typographical errors or misordering of directives. For additional background information about PAM and the syntax of the configuration files involved, refer to <xref linkend=\"cha.pam\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:729
#, no-c-format
msgid "The home partition is encrypted. Find more information about this topic in <xref linkend=\"sec.trouble.login.encrypted\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:735
#, no-c-format
msgid "In all cases that do not involve external network problems, the solution is to reboot the system into single-user mode and repair the configuration before booting again into operating mode and attempting to log in again. To boot into single-user mode:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:743
#, no-c-format
msgid "Reboot the system. The boot screen appears, offering a prompt."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:754
#, no-c-format
msgid "Press <keycap function=\"escape\"/> to exit the splash screen and get to the &grub; text-based menu."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:760
#, no-c-format
msgid "Press <keycap>B</keycap> to enter the &grub; editor."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:765
#, no-c-format
msgid "Add the following parameter to the line containing the kernel parameters:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: troubleshooting.xml:768
#, no-c-format
msgid "systemd.unit=rescue.target"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:771
#, no-c-format
msgid "Press <keycap>F10</keycap> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:776
#, no-c-format
msgid "Enter the user name and password for <systemitem class=\"username\">root</systemitem> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:782
#, no-c-format
msgid "Make all the necessary changes."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:787
#, no-c-format
msgid "Boot into the full multiuser and network mode by entering <command>systemctl isolate graphical.target</command> at the command line."
msgstr ""

