#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:962
#, no-c-format
msgid "Determine that the user's user name and password work on other machines to make sure that his authentication data exists and is properly distributed."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:969
#, no-c-format
msgid "See if another user can log in to the misbehaving machine. If another user can log in without difficulty or if <systemitem class=\"username\">root</systemitem> can log in, log in and examine the system journal with <command>journalctl -e</command> &gt; file. Locate the time stamps that correspond to the login attempts and determine if PAM has produced any error messages."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:979
#, no-c-format
msgid "Try to log in from a console (using <keycombo> <keycap function=\"control\"/> <keycap function=\"alt\"/> <keycap>F1</keycap> </keycombo> ). If this is successful, the problem is not with PAM or the directory server on which the user's home is hosted, because it is possible to authenticate this user on this machine. Try to locate any problems with the X Window System or the &gnome; desktop. For more information, refer to <xref linkend=\"sec.trouble.login.dk\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:990
#, no-c-format
msgid "If the user's home directory has been used with another Linux distribution, remove the <filename>Xauthority</filename> file in the user's home. Use a console login via <keycombo> <keycap function=\"control\"/> <keycap function=\"alt\"/> <keycap>F1</keycap> </keycombo> and run <command>rm .Xauthority</command> as this user. This should eliminate X authentication problems for this user. Try graphical login again."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1021
#, no-c-format
msgid "If the desktop could not start because of corrupt configuration files, proceed with <xref linkend=\"sec.trouble.login.dk\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: troubleshooting.xml:1030
#, no-c-format
msgid "Login to Encrypted Home Partition Fails"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1031
#, no-c-format
msgid "It is recommended to use an encrypted home partition for laptops. If you cannot log in to your laptop, the reason is usually simple: your partition could not be unlocked."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1036
#, no-c-format
msgid "During the boot time, you need to enter the passphrase to unlock your encrypted partition. If you do not enter it, the boot process continues, leaving the partition locked."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1041
#, no-c-format
msgid "To unlock your encrypted partition, proceed as follows:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1046
#, no-c-format
msgid "Switch to the text console with <keycombo> <keycap function=\"control\"/> <keycap function=\"alt\"/> <keycap>F1</keycap> </keycombo> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1052
#, no-c-format
msgid "Become <systemitem class=\"username\">root</systemitem> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1057
#, no-c-format
msgid "Restart the unlocking process again with:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: troubleshooting.xml:1060
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.root;systemctl restart home.mount"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1063
#, no-c-format
msgid "Enter your passphrase to unlock your encrypted partition."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1068
#, no-c-format
msgid "Exit the text console and switch back to the login screen with <keycombo> <keycap function=\"alt\"/> <keycap>F7</keycap> </keycombo> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1074
#, no-c-format
msgid "Log in as usual."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: troubleshooting.xml:1082
#, no-c-format
msgid "Login Successful but &gnome; Desktop Fails"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1083
#, no-c-format
msgid "If this is the case, it is likely that your &gnome; configuration files have become corrupted. Some symptoms may include the keyboard failing to work, the screen geometry becoming distorted, or even the screen coming up as a bare gray field. The important distinction is that if another user logs in, the machine works normally. It is then likely that the problem can be fixed relatively quickly by simply moving the user's &gnome; configuration directory to a new location, which causes &gnome; to initialize a new one. Although the user is forced to reconfigure &gnome;, no data is lost."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1096
#, no-c-format
msgid "Switch to a text console by pressing <keycombo> <keycap function=\"control\"/> <keycap function=\"alt\"/> <keycap>F1</keycap> </keycombo> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1103
#, no-c-format
msgid "Log in with your user name."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1108
#, no-c-format
msgid "Move the user's &gnome; configuration directories to a temporary location:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: troubleshooting.xml:1112
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.user;mv .gconf  .gconf-ORIG-RECOVER\n"
      "&prompt.user;mv .gnome2 .gnome2-ORIG-RECOVER"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1116
#, no-c-format
msgid "Log out."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1121
#, no-c-format
msgid "Log in again, but do not run any applications."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1126
#, no-c-format
msgid "Recover your individual application configuration data (including the Evolution e-mail client data) by copying the <filename>~/.gconf-ORIG-RECOVER/apps/</filename> directory back into the new <filename>~/.gconf </filename> directory as follows:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: troubleshooting.xml:1132
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.user;cp -a .gconf-ORIG-RECOVER/apps .gconf/"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1133
#, no-c-format
msgid "If this causes the login problems, attempt to recover only the critical application data and reconfigure the remainder of the applications."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: troubleshooting.xml:1142
#, no-c-format
msgid "Network Problems"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1144
#, no-c-format
msgid "Many problems of your system may be network-related, even though they do not seem to be at first. For example, the reason for a system not allowing users to log in may be a network problem of some kind. This section introduces a simple checklist you can apply to identify the cause of any network problem encountered."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: troubleshooting.xml:1153
#, no-c-format
msgid "How to Identify Network Problems"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1154
#, no-c-format
msgid "When checking the network connection of your machine, proceed as follows:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1158
#, no-c-format
msgid "If you use an Ethernet connection, check the hardware first. Make sure that your network cable is properly plugged into your computer and router (or hub, etc.). The control lights next to your Ethernet connector are normally both be active."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1164
#, no-c-format
msgid "If the connection fails, check whether your network cable works with another machine. If it does, your network card causes the failure. If hubs or switches are included in your network setup, they may be faulty, as well."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1172
#, no-c-format
msgid "If using a wireless connection, check whether the wireless link can be established by other machines. If not, contact the wireless network's administrator."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1179
#, no-c-format
msgid "When you have checked your basic network connectivity, try to find out which service is not responding. Gather the address information of all network servers needed in your setup. Either look them up in the appropriate &yast; module or ask your system administrator. The following list gives some typical network servers involved in a setup together with the symptoms of an outage."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: troubleshooting.xml:1189
#, no-c-format
msgid "DNS (Name Service)"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1191
#, no-c-format
msgid "A broken or malfunctioning name service affects the network's functionality in many ways. If the local machine relies on any network servers for authentication and these servers cannot be found because of name resolution issues, users would not even be able to log in. Machines in the network managed by a broken name server would not be able to <quote>see</quote> each other and communicate."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: troubleshooting.xml:1202
#, no-c-format
msgid "NTP (Time Service)"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1204
#, no-c-format
msgid "A malfunctioning or completely broken NTP service could affect Kerberos authentication and X server functionality."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: troubleshooting.xml:1211
#, no-c-format
msgid "NFS (File Service)"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1213
#, no-c-format
msgid "If any application needs data stored in an NFS mounted directory, it cannot start or function properly if this service was down or misconfigured. In the worst case scenario, a user's personal desktop configuration would not come up if their home directory containing the <filename>.gconf</filename> subdirectory could not be found because of a faulty NFS server."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: troubleshooting.xml:1224
#, no-c-format
msgid "Samba (File Service)"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1226
#, no-c-format
msgid "If any application needs data stored in a directory on a faulty Samba server, it cannot start or function properly."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: troubleshooting.xml:1233
#, no-c-format
msgid "NIS (User Management)"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1235
#, no-c-format
msgid "If your &productname; system relies on a faulty NIS server to provide the user data, users cannot log in to this machine."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: troubleshooting.xml:1242
#, no-c-format
msgid "LDAP (User Management)"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1244
#, no-c-format
msgid "If your &productname; system relies on a faulty LDAP server to provide the user data, users cannot log in to this machine."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: troubleshooting.xml:1251
#, no-c-format
msgid "Kerberos (Authentication)"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1253
#, no-c-format
msgid "Authentication will not work and login to any machine fails."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: troubleshooting.xml:1259
#, no-c-format
msgid "CUPS (Network Printing)"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1261
#, no-c-format
msgid "Users cannot print."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1269
#, no-c-format
msgid "Check whether the network servers are running and whether your network setup allows you to establish a connection:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: troubleshooting.xml:1274
#, no-c-format
msgid "Limitations"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1275
#, no-c-format
msgid "The debugging procedure described below only applies to a simple network server/client setup that does not involve any internal routing. It assumes both server and client are members of the same subnet without the need for additional routing."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1284
#, no-c-format
msgid "Use <command>ping</command> <replaceable>IP_ADDRESS/HOSTNAME</replaceable> (replace with the host name or IP address of the server) to check whether each one of them is up and responding to the network. If this command is successful, it tells you that the host you were looking for is up and running and that the name service for your network is configured correctly."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1293
#, no-c-format
msgid "If ping fails with <literal>destination host unreachable</literal> , either your system or the desired server is not properly configured or down. Check whether your system is reachable by running <command>ping</command> <replaceable>IP address</replaceable> or <replaceable>YOUR_HOSTNAME</replaceable> from another machine. If you can reach your machine from another machine, it is the server that is not running or not configured correctly."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1302
#, no-c-format
msgid "If ping fails with <literal>unknown host</literal> , the name service is not configured correctly or the host name used was incorrect. For further checks on this matter, refer to <xref linkend=\"st.trouble.config.net.host\" xrefstyle=\"StepOnPage\"/> . If ping still fails, either your network card is not configured correctly or your network hardware is faulty."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1312
#, no-c-format
msgid "Use <command>host</command> <replaceable>HOSTNAME</replaceable> to check whether the host name of the server you are trying to connect to is properly translated into an IP address and vice versa. If this command returns the IP address of this host, the name service is up and running. If the <command>host</command> command fails, check all network configuration files relating to name and address resolution on your host:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: troubleshooting.xml:1323
#, no-c-format
msgid "<filename>/etc/resolv.conf</filename>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1326
#, no-c-format
msgid "This file is used to keep track of the name server and domain you are currently using. It can be modified manually or automatically adjusted by &yast; or DHCP. Automatic adjustment is preferable. However, make sure that this file has the following structure and all network addresses and domain names are correct:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: troubleshooting.xml:1333
#, no-c-format
msgid "search <replaceable>FULLY_QUALIFIED_DOMAIN_NAME</replaceable>\n"
      "nameserver <replaceable>IPADDRESS_OF_NAMESERVER</replaceable>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1335
#, no-c-format
msgid "This file can contain more than one name server address, but at least one of them must be correct to provide name resolution to your host. If needed, adjust this file using the &yast; Network Settings module (Hostname/DNS tab)."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1341
#, no-c-format
msgid "If your network connection is handled via DHCP, enable DHCP to change host name and name service information by selecting <guimenu>Set Hostname via DHCP</guimenu> (can be set globally for any interface or per interface) and <guimenu>Update Name Servers and Search List via DHCP</guimenu> in the &yast; Network Settings module (Hostname/DNS tab)."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: troubleshooting.xml:1351
#, no-c-format
msgid "<filename>/etc/nsswitch.conf</filename>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1354
#, no-c-format
msgid "This file tells Linux where to look for name service information. It should look like this:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: troubleshooting.xml:1358
#, no-c-format
msgid " ...\n"
      "hosts: files dns\n"
      "networks: files dns\n"
      "..."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1362
#, no-c-format
msgid "The <option>dns</option> entry is vital. It tells Linux to use an external name server. Normally, these entries are automatically managed by &yast;, but it would be prudent to check."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1367
#, no-c-format
msgid "If all the relevant entries on the host are correct, let your system administrator check the DNS server configuration for the correct zone information. <phrase os=\"sles;osuse\">For detailed information about DNS, refer to <xref linkend=\"cha.dns\"/>.</phrase> If you have made sure that the DNS configuration of your host and the DNS server are correct, proceed with checking the configuration of your network and network device."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1381
#, no-c-format
msgid "If your system cannot establish a connection to a network server and you have excluded name service problems from the list of possible culprits, check the configuration of your network card."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1386
#, no-c-format
msgid "Use the command <command>ip addr show</command> <replaceable>NETWORK_DEVICE</replaceable> to check whether this device was properly configured. Make sure that the <option>inet address</option> with the netmask ( <literal>/<replaceable>MASK</replaceable></literal> ) is configured correctly. An error in the IP address or a missing bit in your network mask would render your network configuration unusable. If necessary, perform this check on the server as well."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1398
#, no-c-format
msgid "If the name service and network hardware are properly configured and running, but some external network connections still get long time-outs or fail entirely, use <command>traceroute</command> <replaceable>FULLY_QUALIFIED_DOMAIN_NAME</replaceable> (executed as <systemitem class=\"username\">root</systemitem> ) to track the network route these requests are taking. This command lists any gateway (hop) that a request from your machine passes on its way to its destination. It lists the response time of each hop and whether this hop is reachable. Use a combination of traceroute and ping to track down the culprit and let the administrators know."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1415
#, no-c-format
msgid "When you have identified the cause of your network trouble, you can resolve it yourself (if the problem is located on your machine) or let the system administrators of your network know about your findings so they can reconfigure the services or repair the necessary systems."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: troubleshooting.xml:1423
#, no-c-format
msgid "&nm; Problems"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1425
#, no-c-format
msgid "If you have a problem with network connectivity, narrow it down as described in <xref linkend=\"proc.trouble.config.net\"/> . If &nm; seems to be the culprit, proceed as follows to get logs providing hints on why &nm; fails:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1433
#, no-c-format
msgid "Open a shell and log in as <systemitem class=\"username\">root</systemitem> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1439
#, no-c-format
msgid "Restart the NetworkManager:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: troubleshooting.xml:1442
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.sudo;systemctl restart NetworkManager"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1445
#, no-c-format
msgid "Open a Web page, for example, <link xlink:href=\"http://www.opensuse.org\"/> as normal user to see, if you can connect."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1452
#, no-c-format
msgid "Collect any information about the state of NetworkManager in <filename>/var/log/NetworkManager</filename> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1458
#, no-c-format
msgid "For more information about NetworkManager, refer to <xref linkend=\"cha.nm\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: troubleshooting.xml:1465
#, no-c-format
msgid "Data Problems"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1467
#, no-c-format
msgid "Data problems are when the machine may or may not boot properly but, in either case, it is clear that there is data corruption on the system and that the system needs to be recovered. These situations call for a backup of your critical data, enabling you to recover the system state from before your system failed."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: troubleshooting.xml:1476
#, no-c-format
msgid "Managing Partition Images"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1477
#, no-c-format
msgid "Sometimes you need to perform a backup from an entire partition or even hard disk. Linux comes with the <command>dd</command> tool which can create an exact copy of your disk. Combined with <command>gzip</command> you save some space."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: troubleshooting.xml:1484
#, no-c-format
msgid "Backing up and Restoring Hard Disks"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1486
#, no-c-format
msgid "Start a Shell as user &rootuser;."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1491
#, no-c-format
msgid "Select your source device. Typically this is something like <filename>/dev/sda</filename> (labeled as <replaceable>SOURCE</replaceable> )."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1498
#, no-c-format
msgid "Decide where you want to store your image (labeled as <replaceable>BACKUP_PATH</replaceable> ). It must be different from your source device. In other words: if you make a backup from <filename>/dev/sda</filename> , your image file must not to be stored under <filename>/dev/sda</filename> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1507
#, no-c-format
msgid "Run the commands to create a compressed image file:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: troubleshooting.xml:1510
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.root;dd if=/dev/<replaceable>SOURCE</replaceable> | gzip &gt; /<replaceable>BACKUP_PATH</replaceable>/image.gz"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1513
#, no-c-format
msgid "Restore the hard disk with the following commands:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: troubleshooting.xml:1516
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.root;gzip -dc /<replaceable>BACKUP_PATH</replaceable>/image.gz | dd of=/dev/<replaceable>SOURCE</replaceable>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: troubleshooting.xml:1519
#, no-c-format
msgid "If you only need to back up a partition, replace the <replaceable>SOURCE</replaceable> placeholder with your respective partition. In this case, your image file can lie on the same hard disk, but on a different partition."
msgstr ""

